  <h2>What is a Computer?</h2>
  <p>
    A <strong>computer</strong> is an electronic machine that can receive information (called <em>input</em>), process it, store it, and show results (called <em>output</em>). Computers follow instructions written by people — these instructions are called <strong>programs</strong> or <strong>software</strong>.
  </p>
  <p>
    Computers are everywhere! Your smartphone, tablet, smart TV, school laptop, and even your microwave all have tiny computers inside them. They help us learn, communicate, play, and solve problems every day.
  </p>

  <h2>How Does a Computer Work?</h2>
  <p>Every computer does four basic things, in this order:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>📥 <strong>Input</strong> — You give the computer information (typing on a keyboard, clicking a mouse, speaking into a microphone).</li>
    <li>⚙️ <strong>Processing</strong> — The CPU (brain of the computer) thinks about the information and figures out what to do.</li>
    <li>💾 <strong>Storage</strong> — The computer remembers information on its hard drive or in RAM.</li>
    <li>📤 <strong>Output</strong> — The computer shows you the result on the screen, through speakers, or by printing.</li>
  </ul>

  <blockquote>
    Think of a computer like a chef: you give the chef ingredients (<strong>input</strong>), they cook it (<strong>processing</strong>), they keep the recipe in a notebook (<strong>storage</strong>), and serve you the meal (<strong>output</strong>)!
  </blockquote>

  <h2>The Two Main Parts of Every Computer</h2>
  <p>Every computer — big or small — is made of two key things:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>🔧 <strong>Hardware</strong> — Physical parts you can touch and see, like the screen, keyboard, mouse, and chips inside.</li>
    <li>💿 <strong>Software</strong> — Programs and apps that run on the computer, like games, browsers, drawing tools, and the operating system (Windows, macOS, Android).</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Hardware and software work together like a body and a brain — neither is useful without the other!</p>

  <h2>Main Parts of a Computer</h2>
  <p>Let's explore the important parts you'll find in most computers:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>🖥️ <strong>Monitor (Screen)</strong> — The display that shows you everything. It is the computer's output device.</li>
    <li>⌨️ <strong>Keyboard</strong> — Used to type letters, numbers, and commands. It is an input device.</li>
    <li>🖱️ <strong>Mouse</strong> — Lets you point, click, and drag things on screen. Also an input device.</li>
    <li>🧠 <strong>CPU (Central Processing Unit)</strong> — The "brain" of the computer. It processes all instructions and calculations.</li>
    <li>💾 <strong>RAM (Memory)</strong> — Temporary memory that holds information the CPU is actively using right now.</li>
    <li>📦 <strong>Hard Drive / SSD (Storage)</strong> — Where all your files, photos, games, and apps are saved permanently.</li>
    <li>🎴 <strong>Motherboard</strong> — The main circuit board that connects all the parts together.</li>
    <li>🖼️ <strong>GPU (Graphics Card)</strong> — Handles drawing images and videos on your screen, especially in games.</li>
    <li>🔌 <strong>Power Supply Unit (PSU)</strong> — Converts electricity from the wall outlet into power the computer can use.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Types of Computers</h2>
  <p>Computers come in many shapes and sizes! Here are the most common types:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>🖥️ <strong>Desktop Computer</strong> — Sits on a desk. Has separate monitor, keyboard, and mouse. Very powerful for school, work, and gaming.</li>
    <li>💻 <strong>Laptop</strong> — A portable computer with a built-in screen, keyboard, and battery. You can take it anywhere!</li>
    <li>📱 <strong>Smartphone</strong> — A tiny but powerful computer that fits in your pocket. You can call, text, browse the web, and use apps.</li>
    <li>📟 <strong>Tablet</strong> — Like a big smartphone with a touchscreen, usually used for reading, drawing, and browsing.</li>
    <li>⌚ <strong>Smartwatch</strong> — A computer worn on your wrist! It tracks your steps, shows notifications, and tells time.</li>
    <li>🎮 <strong>Gaming Console</strong> — Computers designed just for playing video games (like PlayStation, Xbox, or Nintendo Switch).</li>
    <li>🌐 <strong>Server</strong> — Extremely powerful computers that store websites and data for millions of people at once.</li>
    <li>🏭 <strong>Supercomputer</strong> — The most powerful computers in the world, used by scientists to model weather, space, and diseases.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>A Short History of Computers</h2>
  <p>Computers weren't always small! Here's a quick look at how they evolved:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>🏛️ <strong>1940s</strong> — Early computers like ENIAC filled entire rooms and weighed 30 tons!</li>
    <li>📺 <strong>1970s</strong> — The first personal computers (PCs) were invented. Now people could have a computer at home.</li>
    <li>🖱️ <strong>1984</strong> — Apple released the Macintosh, making computers easier to use with pictures and a mouse.</li>
    <li>🌐 <strong>1990s</strong> — The Internet became popular, connecting computers around the whole world.</li>
    <li>📱 <strong>2007</strong> — Apple launched the iPhone, making powerful computers fit in our pockets.</li>
    <li>🤖 <strong>Today</strong> — AI (Artificial Intelligence) makes computers smarter than ever!</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Why Are Computers Important?</h2>
  <p>Computers help humans do amazing things:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>📚 <strong>Education</strong> — Students learn coding, maths, and science with interactive programs.</li>
    <li>🏥 <strong>Medicine</strong> — Doctors use computers to diagnose diseases and guide robotic surgery.</li>
    <li>🚀 <strong>Space Exploration</strong> — NASA uses computers to navigate spacecraft to other planets.</li>
    <li>🎨 <strong>Art & Music</strong> — Artists create digital paintings, animations, and music using computers.</li>
    <li>🔗 <strong>Communication</strong> — Video calls, emails, and messaging apps connect people across the world instantly.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Fun Facts About Computers</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>🤯 The first computer "bug" was a real bug — a moth was found inside a computer in 1947!</li>
    <li>⚡ A modern smartphone is millions of times more powerful than the computers used to send astronauts to the Moon in 1969.</li>
    <li>🌍 There are more than 4 billion computers in use around the world today.</li>
    <li>🧮 The word "computer" originally meant a <em>person</em> who did math calculations by hand!</li>
    <li>💡 The average person spends about 7 hours a day in front of a computer screen.</li>
  </ul>

